  "prompt": "Is there anything faster than the speed of light?",
  "response": "According to our current understanding of physics, nothing can travel faster than the speed of light in a vacuum, which is approximately 299,792 kilometers per second (about 186,282 miles per second). This is a fundamental principle of Einstein's theory of relativity. \n\nThere have been various theoretical proposals and speculative concepts in physics, such as tachyons (hypothetical particles that travel faster than light) and phenomena like quantum entanglement, where changes seem to occur instantaneously at a distance. However, none of these concepts have been observed or proven to violate the speed of light limit for information or matter travel.\n\nTherefore, as of now, light speed remains the ultimate speed limit in the universe according to our best scientific understanding.",
